[SN]TITLE[SN]
Scottish property market sees decade of 'highs and lows'

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
The last 10 years has seen a mixture of "highs and lows" in the Scottish property market, according to a new report.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
Registers of Scotland (RoS) research found the market had largely weathered the financial crash of 2007-08, with average prices now at their highest level in 10 years.
However, the volume of sales is down by 35% over the decade.
The report also shows that the number of cash sales has increased.
The RoS data details trends in the property market during the period between 2005 and 2015, and covers detached, semi-detached, terraces and flats.
RoS is the government department responsible for compiling and maintaining registers related to land and property.
